example: heated cylinder in a square cavity
===========================================

> Note: the directory is cylindrical-cht/ but the case is
> not a CHT problem. It's natural convection in a single
> incompressible fluid region — there's no solid wall to conduct
> through. The "cylindrical" part refers to the heated cylinder
> geometry inside the cavity. We recommend renaming the directory
> to heated-cylinder-cavity/ before the public release; see the
> note at the bottom.

A classical buoyancy benchmark: a hot cylinder at the centre of a
2D square cavity drives natural convection plumes that rise off
the cylinder, hit the top wall, descend along the cold side walls,
and circulate back to the bottom. No imposed flow — the velocity
field is entirely buoyancy-induced.


<img src="../images/cylindrical-cht.png" width="700" alt="natural convection around a heated cylinder, temperature field">


what it teaches
---------------

  - how buoyantBoussinesqSimpleFoam differs from the fully-
    compressible buoyant solvers — density varies only in the
    buoyancy source term (Boussinesq approximation), everywhere
    else ρ = ρ_ref
  - how T_ref and β (thermal expansion coefficient) enter
    constant/transportProperties — these are inputs that don't
    exist for non-buoyant solvers
  - how a closed cavity flows through the BC pipeline — no
    _inlet or _outlet patches, just cylinder (hot wall) and
    walls (cold walls). flow_kind would be "closed" in a
    multi-region equivalent, but for this single-region case
    that's not surfaced
  - how 0/p_rgh differs from 0/p for buoyant flows
    (p_rgh = p - ρ_ref·g·h) and which one is the solved variable
  - why natural convection needs many more iterations to
    converge than forced flow at the same Re — the buoyancy
    coupling is weaker than imposed inlet momentum


the prompt
----------

The full prompt is in examples/cylindrical-cht/prompt.txt. The
load-bearing clauses:

  - solver: Use buoyantBoussinesqSimpleFoam
  - geometry: 1 m × 1 m cavity, cylinder r = 0.1 m centered
  - BCs: cylinder at 350 K, outer walls at 300 K, no inlets
  - 2D: front/back empty
  - gravity: −y, 9.81
  - fluid props: β = 3.4e-3, ν = 1.5e-5, Pr = 0.7, T_ref = 300
  - turbulence: kOmegaSST, 5% intensity, ℓ = 0.07 m
  - control: 3000 iter, 1e-5 residual, write every 200


what the agent does
-------------------

  1. Precheck: parses the closed-cavity topology. The
     boundary planner sees no inlet patches, so no
     flowRateInletVelocity or fixedValue (U=...) BCs get
     stamped. Cylinder and outer-wall patches receive
     fixedValue T = 350 / fixedValue T = 300 respectively.
     U on every patch defaults to noSlip (closed walls).

  2. Lints: detects steady (3000 iter mentioned, no end time),
     buoyant (gravity acts in −y, flow is driven entirely by
     buoyancy), Boussinesq (explicit β + T_ref + ν + Pr — the
     classical Boussinesq inputs). Turbulent because the prompt
     names kOmegaSST.

  3. Selects: prompt says Use buoyantBoussinesqSimpleFoam,
     selector LLM is skipped. The selector would have picked the
     same anyway — gravity + closed cavity + ΔT/T < 0.2 + steady
     unambiguously points at Boussinesq.

  4. Generates ~10 files:
     system/{controlDict,fvSchemes,fvSolution},
     constant/{transportProperties,turbulenceProperties,g},
     0/{U,p_rgh,T,k,omega,nut,alphat}.

       - constant/transportProperties carries the Boussinesq
         block: transportModel Newtonian; nu 1.5e-5; beta 3.4e-3;
         TRef 300; Pr 0.7; Prt 0.85;.
       - constant/g is (0 -9.81 0).
       - 0/p_rgh is the solved variable. 0/p is not
         generated — Boussinesq treats density as constant so a
         separate hydrostatic pressure file isn't needed.

  5. Validates (auto-fixes that fire for this case):
       - 0/T internalField = 300 (matches the cold-wall T_ref —
         the validator catches a default 300 K choice that happens
         to be right here, but would have clamped it had the
         user specified a different T_ref).
       - endTime = 3000, writeInterval = 200,
         writeControl = timeStep.
       - residualControl { p_rgh 1e-5; U 1e-5; T 1e-5; ... }.
       - kOmegaSST relaxation factors set conservatively
         (under-relax for slow buoyant coupling).

  6. Submits: sim-server runs buoyantBoussinesqSimpleFoam.
     The first ~500 iterations show residuals fall fast as the
     temperature field equilibrates; then a long plateau as the
     plume settles into its steady recirculation pattern. Full
     convergence to 1e-5 usually lands between 2000–3000
     iterations.

Typical runtime: 60–90 seconds codegen, 8–20 minutes solver.


to reproduce
------------

From the frontend (http://localhost:3000):

  1. New project → upload
     examples/cylindrical-cht/mesh/cylindrical-cht.msh.
  2. Paste examples/cylindrical-cht/prompt.txt.
  3. Click Run.

Or directly with OpenFOAM:

    cd examples/cylindrical-cht/case
    buoyantBoussinesqSimpleFoam


what you should see
-------------------

A buoyant plume rising off the top of the cylinder, fanning out
against the top wall, and descending along the two side walls.
Near the bottom of the cavity the flow recirculates inward toward
the cylinder's underside, where it warms again and rises.

The temperature field is sharpest right at the cylinder surface
(thin thermal boundary layer) and smoothly decays toward the cold
outer walls. The velocity magnitude is highest in the rising plume
just above the cylinder and in the descending sheets along the
side walls.

This setup has Ra (Rayleigh) ≈ g·β·ΔT·L³ / (ν·α) ≈
9.81 × 3.4e-3 × 50 × 1³ / (1.5e-5 × 2.14e-5) ≈ 5×10⁹ — well into
the turbulent natural convection regime, which is why kOmegaSST
is the right choice over laminar.


what's NOT modeled
------------------

  - Radiation. At ΔT = 50 K and air, radiative heat transfer
    is a few percent of convective and ignoring it is fine.
    For higher ΔT or low-emissivity walls, switch to a solver with
    radiation (buoyantSimpleFoam + fvOptions radiation or
    similar).
  - Compressibility. Boussinesq assumes ΔT/T_ref < 0.1ish.
    Here ΔT/T_ref ≈ 50/300 = 0.17, so we're at the edge of
    Boussinesq's validity. For higher ΔT use the fully-compressible
    buoyantSimpleFoam instead.


on the directory name
---------------------

This directory was originally named cylindrical-cht/ when the
plan was for a concentric-tube CHT regasifier (multi-region, like
inner-outer-pipe/). The actual case here is single-region
natural convection, which is a completely different solver and
physics regime.

Two options:

  - Rename the directory to better reflect what's inside.
    Candidates: heated-cylinder-cavity/,
    natural-convection-cavity/, boussinesq-cavity/.
    Recommended for the public release.

  - Keep the name and just live with the misnomer. Lower
    cost, but every reader will be confused.

If you rename, four files need updates besides the directory
itself:

  - README.md            (the examples/ block)
  - Documentation/examples/README  (the table)
  - Documentation/examples/cylindrical-cht  → rename
  - examples/cylindrical-cht/README  (cross-references)
